tion":0.04,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.83,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The tone re-check correctly identifies when a response is too formal for a casual-tier customer and triggers regeneration.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"At least one real model decision is required: tone identification ('too formal for a casual-tier customer') is AI judgment. MOCK-HIDE: mocked classifier would mask misclassification. Orchestration to trigger regeneration is important, but only one agentic decision governs handoff, so Agentic is sufficient (not necessarily Workflow). REJECTION-GATE: rejected Integration because concrete behavior text requires correctness of tone identification, which a deterministic stub cannot validate; rejected Workflow because behavior does not require validating multiple model decisions’ combined quality, only that identification causes regeneration.","test_description":"Provide cases with intentionally formal drafts for casual-tier customers, run the real tone-check model, and assert it flags and causes a regeneration call; verify regeneration path executes when flagged.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.14,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.68,"Workflow":0.15}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The full exchange (user message, generated response, any regenerations) is persisted to the database with correct timestamps.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure is at module handoff between chat orchestration and persistence layer, requiring real repository/DB wiring. Unit is too low because ordering/transaction/timestamp mapping bugs appear across components. REAL-INFRA: local DB is enough; no real external network/subprocess required. LLM output quality is irrelevant; fixed strings can be used. REJECTION-GATE: rejected System because behavior text is DB persistence semantics ('persisted ... with correct timestamps'), which can be caught with in-process integration DB tests.","test_description":"Execute chat flow with a forced regeneration using deterministic model stubs, write records to a test DB, then assert all entries exist (user, first draft, regenerated draft/final) with correct timestamp fields and ordering.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.79,"System":0.11,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the tone check triggers regeneration, the second response replaces the first — the customer never sees the rejected draft.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Primary failure boundary is orchestration/state handoff across local modules (tone-check result -> response selector -> outbound message). This is more than one function, so Unit may miss wiring bugs. LLM-DEP: not required if trigger condition and responses are controlled fixtures. MULTI-STEP agentic pipeline is not required to validate replacement semantics. REJECTION-GATE: rejected Agentic/Workflow because behavior text is visibility/selection logic ('second response replaces the first') rather than model output quality.","test_description":"With deterministic stubs, force tone-check=triggered, return distinct first/second drafts, run end-to-end service path, and assert outbound payload/customer-visible response is only the second draft while first is retained only in internal logs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.11,"Workflow":0.04}}]}
